         <abstract>
            <p>This paper presents the results of a survey of cost of capital techniques used by 177 firms responding to a questionnaire sent to all firms in the 1980 Fortune 1000 listing. The questionnaire contained 21 closed-end questions providing a total of 121 data items. The responses reported in the paper provide interesting and somewhat disheartening results, in that they reflect a reluctance on the part of financial management practitioners to employ many of the cost of capital techniques that are often considered "common practice" by finance academicians. The five-part paper presents 1) the survey methodology and profiles of the respondents; 2) cost of capital measurement techniques; 3) findings relative to the consideration given by respondents to risk; 4) the cost of capital administration procedures employed by respondents; and 5) summary and conclusions.</p>
         </abstract>
